BBC Breaking News: "There will be no further Covid restrictions in England before the new year, UK Health Secretary Sajid Javid says, but he urges people to "remain cautious""
https://twitter.com/BBCBreaking/status/1475509168362737664
@Anneinak

For this to happen, there needs to be : 
1/ a heightened risk;
2/ political will to tackle the situation through those measures. 1/ Even though the number of cases may still be quite high, the number of deaths remains largely subdued (compared to where it used to be when the number of cases was this high). Furthermore, the number of cases seems to be stalling (weak evidence). Appearance of new variants is unlikely to change this, since delta seems to be mitigated by the vaccine as well, and variants take time to spread.  2/ The right criterion to think about this is the number of deaths. The number of cases peaked right around "Freedom Day", so it is unlikely to be used as a reason to reintroduce measures soon. In political terms, the government has taken a strong stance and it would be difficult to go back to containment measures.  The 2nd and 3rd lockdowns were triggered at a time were deaths were rising fast and at levels of 0.5 and 1 (per 100000) respectively. I estimate the probability of this happening again before EOY at 10% at most (considering the slow and continuous rise of deaths, which may be due to a high number of cases on non-vaccinated people).  For this to then politically be used to justify lockdowns, I would give a probability of 50% (same level as before, but now commitment to stay open).  Combined, this gives a 5% probability.
